## 3. Database Design Recommendations

### Constraints

| Table | Constraint | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| `user` | `email` | UNIQUE | Prevent duplicate accounts |
| `user` | `role IN (…)` | CHECK | Enforce valid role enum |
| `branch` | `name` | UNIQUE | No duplicate branch names |
| `service_type` | `name` | UNIQUE | No duplicate service names |
| `staff_service_type` | `(staff_id, service_type_id)` | UNIQUE COMPOSITE | Prevent duplicate assignments |
| `slot` | `(branch_id, service_type_id, slot_date, start_time)` | UNIQUE COMPOSITE | Prevent duplicate slot definitions |
| `slot` | `start_time < end_time` | CHECK | Logical time ordering |
| `slot` | `current_bookings <= max_bookings` | CHECK | Integrity guard |
| `appointment` | `status IN (…)` | CHECK | Valid state transitions |
| `system_settings` | `key` | UNIQUE | One value per setting |

### Indexes

```sql
-- Performance-critical queries
CREATE INDEX idx_slot_lookup
  ON slot (branch_id, service_type_id, slot_date, is_active)
  WHERE deleted_at IS NULL;

CREATE INDEX idx_appointment_customer
  ON appointment (customer_id, status);

CREATE INDEX idx_appointment_slot
  ON appointment (slot_id, status);

CREATE INDEX idx_audit_entity
  ON audit_log (entity_type, entity_id);

CREATE INDEX idx_audit_timestamp
  ON audit_log (created_at DESC);

CREATE INDEX idx_user_email
  ON "user" (email);

CREATE INDEX idx_user_branch
  ON "user" (branch_id) WHERE branch_id IS NOT NULL;
```

### General Recommendations

- **Use UUIDs (v4)** as primary keys — avoids sequential guessing and makes multi-node merging trivial.
- **All timestamps in UTC** — convert to `Asia/Muscat` (GMT+4) only at the API response layer.
- **Use `timestamptz`** in PostgreSQL for all timestamp columns.
- **Naming**: snake_case for tables/columns; singular table names (`user`, `slot`).
- **Foreign keys with `ON DELETE RESTRICT`** — prevent accidental cascade; handle deletion in business logic.

---

## 4. Soft Delete Strategy

### Design

Soft delete applies to **Slots** (and optionally users/branches if business requires it).

| Column | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `is_active` | `boolean DEFAULT true` | Quick filter for active records |
| `deleted_at` | `timestamptz NULL` | `NULL` = not deleted; timestamp = when deleted |

### Access Pattern

```
-- Application queries ALWAYS filter:
WHERE deleted_at IS NULL AND is_active = true
```

The DAL/repository layer wraps this by default so developers never forget.

### Retention & Permanent Purge

The `system_settings` table stores a key like:

| key | value | description |
|---|---|---|
| `slot_retention_days` | `90` | Days to keep soft-deleted slots before permanent purge |

A **scheduled job** (cron or `pg_cron`) runs periodically:

```
DELETE FROM slot
WHERE deleted_at IS NOT NULL
  AND deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '${retention_days} days';
```

### Rules

1. Soft-deleted slots **cannot** accept new bookings.
2. Existing appointments on a soft-deleted slot remain valid (graceful wind-down).
3. Only **Admin** or **Branch Manager** can soft-delete slots.
4. Permanent purge only runs after verifying no open appointments reference the slot.

---

## 5. Booking Logic — Preventing Double Booking

This is the **most critical section** of the system. Race conditions here cause real business damage.

### Flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["Customer selects slot"] --> B{"Slot exists & is_active & not deleted?"}
    B -- No --> C["Return 404 / 410"]
    B -- Yes --> D{"current_bookings < max_bookings?"}
    D -- No --> E["Return 409 Conflict: Slot Full"]
    D -- Yes --> F["BEGIN TRANSACTION"]
    F --> G["SELECT ... FROM slot WHERE id = $1 FOR UPDATE"]
    G --> H{"Re-check: current_bookings < max_bookings?"}
    H -- No --> I["ROLLBACK → 409 Conflict"]
    H -- Yes --> J["INSERT appointment (status = 'booked')"]
    J --> K["UPDATE slot SET current_bookings = current_bookings + 1"]
    K --> L["COMMIT"]
    L --> M["Return 201 Created"]
```

### Key Mechanism: Pessimistic Locking

```sql
BEGIN;

-- Lock the specific slot row — other transactions WAIT here
SELECT * FROM slot
WHERE id = $1
  AND is_active = true
  AND deleted_at IS NULL
FOR UPDATE;

-- Double-check capacity inside the lock
-- If current_bookings >= max_bookings → ROLLBACK

-- Otherwise:
INSERT INTO appointment (...) VALUES (...);
UPDATE slot SET current_bookings = current_bookings + 1;

COMMIT;
```

> **Why `FOR UPDATE`?** It acquires a row-level exclusive lock. Any concurrent transaction trying to book the same slot will **block** until this transaction commits or rolls back. This is the standard enterprise pattern for inventory-style problems.

### Additional Safeguards

| Safeguard | Implementation |
|---|---|
| **DB-level CHECK** | `current_bookings <= max_bookings` — last line of defense |
| **Idempotency** | Unique constraint `(customer_id, slot_id)` WHERE status = 'booked' — same customer can't double-book the same slot |
| **Cancellation** | Sets `status = 'cancelled'`, decrements `current_bookings` — also inside a transaction |
| **Reschedule** | Cancel old + Book new in a **single transaction** — atomic swap |
| **Stale reads** | API return `current_bookings` so UI can show availability, but the lock is the source of truth |

---

## 6. Role & Permission Matrix

### Roles

| Role | Scope | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **Admin** | System-wide | Full control, multi-branch oversight |
| **Branch Manager** | Single branch | Manages staff, slots, and appointments for their branch |
| **Staff** | Single branch | Views assigned appointments, marks completion |
| **Customer** | Own data | Books/cancels/reschedules own appointments |

### Permission Matrix

| Resource / Action | Admin | Branch Manager | Staff | Customer |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Branches** — Create | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Branches** — Read All | ✅ | ✅ own | ❌ | ✅ list only |
| **Branches** — Update | ✅ | ✅ own | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Branches** — Delete | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Users** — Create Staff | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Users** — Read | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ✅ self | ✅ self |
| **Users** — Update | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ✅ self | ✅ self |
| **Users** — Deactivate | ✅ | ✅ own branch staff | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Service Types** — CRUD | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Staff ↔ Service** — Assign | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Slots** — Create | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Slots** — Read | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ✅ own branch | ✅ available only |
| **Slots** — Update | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Slots** — Soft Delete | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ❌ |
| **Appointments** — Book | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ self |
| **Appointments** — Cancel | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ✅ own |
| **Appointments** — Reschedule | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ❌ | ✅ own |
| **Appointments** — Complete | ✅ | ✅ own branch | ✅ assigned | ❌ |
| **Appointments** — Read | ✅ all | ✅ own branch | ✅ assigned | ✅ own |
| **Audit Logs** — Read | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| **System Settings** — CRUD | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| **File Upload** | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ own |

### Implementation Approach

```
Middleware chain:  authenticate(jwt) → authorize(roles, scopeCheck)
```

- **`authenticate`** — verifies JWT, attaches `req.user = { id, role, branch_id }`.
- **`authorize(allowedRoles)`** — checks if `req.user.role` is in the allowed list.
- **`scopeCheck`** — for Branch Managers and Staff, verify they operate within their own branch:
  ```
  if (user.role === 'branch_manager' && resource.branch_id !== user.branch_id)
      → 403 Forbidden
  ```

